TkSuQmCC"/></span></p><p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:8pt;border:none;mso-border-left-alt:none;mso-border-top-alt:none;mso-border-right-alt:none;mso-border-bottom-alt:none;mso-border-between:none">&nbsp;</p><h2 style="line-height:normal;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:8pt;border:none;mso-border-left-alt:none;mso-border-top-alt:none;mso-border-right-alt:none;mso-border-bottom-alt:none;mso-border-between:none"><a name="_heading=h.slsprvtpiut3"/><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:18pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000"><b>Ensure your SPARQL endpoint is CORS-enabled, or use a proxy</b></span></h2><h3 style="line-height:normal;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:8pt;border:none;mso-border-left-alt:none;mso-border-top-alt:none;mso-border-right-alt:none;mso-border-bottom-alt:none;mso-border-between:none"><a name="_heading=h.4eh7s7osnl86"/><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:13.5pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000"><b>Why do we need CORS ?</b></span></h3><p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:8pt;border:none;mso-border-left-alt:none;mso-border-top-alt:none;mso-border-right-alt:none;mso-border-bottom-alt:none;mso-border-between:none"><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000">CORS stands for Cross-Origin Resource Sharing. It is a mechanism by which a web client can retrieve resources from a different server from the one which it was originally loaded</span><a style="mso-footnote-id:ftn3" href="#_ftn3" name="_ftnref3" title=""><span class="MsoFootnoteReference" style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000;vertical-align:super"><span style="mso-special-character:footnote">[3]</span></span></a><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000">. With CORS, servers can indicate that they allow clients loaded from another domain (or from certain other domains) to send them requests. Note that this restriction applies to client-server interactions, not to server-server interactions.</span></p><p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:8pt;border:none;mso-border-left-alt:none;mso-border-top-alt:none;mso-border-right-alt:none;mso-border-bottom-alt:none;mso-border-between:none"><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000">In the case of Sparnatural, </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000"><u>it is the HTML page that sends the SPARQL query directly to a SPARQL service</u></span><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000">. Th</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000">is SPARQL service thus needs to allow clients/webpages to send queries to it even if they are loaded from another domain, otherwise the query will simply fail with a security warning, and you can see security errors in the requests of your browser console.</span></p><p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:8pt;border:none;mso-border-left-alt:none;mso-border-top-alt:none;mso-border-right-alt:none;mso-border-bottom-alt:none;mso-border-between:none"><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000">You thus need to </span><span from the same domain as the SPARQL endpoint.</span></p><h3 You should deploy your own SPARQL proxy in that case. The code of the SPARQL proxy server is open-source in </span><a href="https://github.com/sparna-git/sparql-proxy" title="https://github.com/sparna-git/sparql-proxy"><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#1155cc;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#1155cc"><u>its own Github repository</u></span></a><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000">, just in case.</span></p><p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:8pt;border:none;mso-border-left-alt:none;mso-border-top-alt:none;mso-border-right-alt:none;mso-border-bottom-alt:none;mso-border-between:none">&nbsp;</p><h2 style="line-height:normal;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:8pt;border:none;mso-border-left-alt:none;mso-border-top-alt:none;mso-border-right-alt:none;mso-border-bottom-alt:none;mso-border-between:none"><a name="_heading=h.u9mj9hqmx97m"/><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:18pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000"><b>Point the tutorial page to your SPARQL service</b></span></h2><p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:8pt;border:none;mso-border-left-alt:none;mso-border-top-alt:none;mso-border-right-alt:none;mso-border-bottom-alt:none;mso-border-between:none"><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000">Now that you have 1. adjusted the security settings of your browser and 2. enabled CORS on your triplestore (or used a proxy), it is time to point the tutorial page to your endpoint !</span></p><p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:8pt;border:none;mso-border-left-alt:none;mso-border-top-alt:none;mso-border-right-alt:none;mso-border-bottom-alt:none;mso-border-between:none"><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000">To do this, edit the index.html file, and search for the “&lt;spar-natural” HTML element name (around line 68)&nbsp; style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:8pt;border:none;mso-border-left-alt:none;mso-border-top-alt:none;mso-border-right-alt:none;mso-border-bottom-alt:none;mso-border-between:none"><span href="http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/" title="http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/"><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#1155cc;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#1155cc"><u>FOAF</u></span></a><span property foaf:member. You will need to adapt the identifiers with your own URI identifiers.</span></p><p style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:8pt;border:none;mso-border-left-alt:none;mso-border-top-alt:none;mso-border-right-alt:none;mso-border-bottom-alt:none;mso-border-between:none"><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000">First you need to create a class for each kind of entity : Organization and Person. You can enter the definition of the foaf:Person class </span><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000"><i>“The </i></span><span style="font-family:'Roboto Mono';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000"><i>foaf:Person</i></span><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000"><i> class represents people. Something is a </i></span><span style="font-family:'Roboto Mono';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000"><i>foaf:Person</i></span><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000"><i> if it is a person. We don&apos;t nitpic about whether they&apos;re alive, dead, real, or imaginary.”</i></span></p></li><li style="list-style-type: decimal"><p style="margin-left:36pt;text-indent:-18pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;border:none;border-left:none;border-top:none;border-right:none;border-bottom:none;mso-border-between:none"><span style="font-family:'Calibri';font-size:11pt;color:#000000;mso-style-textfill-fill-color:#000000">Add a third annotation to set the icon.
